# Executive Escalation Criteria

Items should be escalated to executive leadership when:

- High-risk exposure exceeds tolerance
- Critical remediation activities are overdue
- Regulatory exposure increases
- Major incidents occur
- Critical vendors experience security incidents
- Governance metrics fall below thresholds

---

# Governance Committee Reporting

Governance committees should receive:

## Quarterly Reporting

- Enterprise risk posture
- Significant risk changes
- Risk acceptance decisions
- Program effectiveness metrics
- Regulatory developments

---

## Annual Reporting

- Governance maturity assessment
- Strategic risk trends
- Audit readiness assessment
- Program performance review
- Long-term improvement initiatives

---

# Board Reporting Model

Board reporting should remain strategic.

Recommended topics:

- Top organizational risks
- Regulatory exposure
- Material incidents
- Enterprise risk trends
- Governance program effectiveness
- Strategic recommendations

Boards should not receive operational-level reporting.

---

# Leadership Decision Framework

Leadership reporting should support decisions involving:

- Risk acceptance
- Resource allocation
- Governance priorities
- Compliance initiatives
- Strategic investments
- Vendor risk decisions

---

# Reporting Quality Standards

Leadership reporting should be:

- Accurate
- Consistent
- Timely
- Actionable
- Traceable
- Business-focused

Reports should prioritize clarity over volume.

---

